{
  "answer": "**The Sanskrit term *dharmaśāstra* (धर्मशास्त्र) designates a specific genre of ancient Indic smṛti texts—such as the *Manusmṛti*, *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, and others in this corpus—that systematically codify *dharma* (धर्म), the multifaceted concept of righteous order, duty, ethics, law, ritual obligations, social norms, penance, and kingship.**[^1][^2]\n\nUnlike \"lawbook,\" which connotes a narrow, secular legal compilation focused on statutes, penalties, and court procedures (as in Roman or modern civil codes), *dharmaśāstra* embeds juridical rules within a broader cosmic and soteriological framework derived from Vedic authority. It prescribes not just dispute resolution or crimes but varṇa-āśrama duties (caste-stage obligations), purificatory rites (*prāyaścitta*), ancestral offerings (*śrāddha*), and moral conduct for householders, ascetics, and rulers—aiming at personal purity, ancestral satisfaction, and societal harmony.[^3]\n\n\"Religious code,\" by contrast, implies a dogmatic creed or ecclesiastical rules (e.g., canon law), overly theological and divorced from worldly governance. *Dharmaśāstra* integrates \"religious\" elements (e.g., sacraments, penances) with pragmatic social engineering: inheritance, marriage alliances, royal taxation, and environmental ethics (e.g., cow protection). It is \"revealed\" via smṛti tradition, not divine fiat, and admits interpretive flexibility via assemblies (*pariṣad*).\n\nThe term thus evokes a living, authoritative *śāstra* (treatise/science) corpus—37 works here span authors like Manu and Aṅgirasa—guiding holistic life from cradle to cremation, irreducible to Western binaries of law vs. religion.[^4] No single English gloss captures this; it names texts as *dharma*'s \"sciences,\" binding eternal norms to contingent practice. The corpus lacks exhaustive coverage of every subtopic, but these texts self-identify as *dharmaśāstra*, illuminating their unique scope.[^5]",
